+For `exit_code_only` tmux launches, a missing or late `.done` is not generic
+success. A caller may opt into a fail-closed completion verifier. Hive first
+requires a live/readable pane at a finished prompt, sends a bounded `/quit`,
+and requires the wrapper sidecar to report status `0`. The stage must then
+prove its own outputs. Review fix is the first strict consumer: it requires
+current-pass reviewer and escalation artifacts, no unresolved escalation or
+reviewer error artifact, a clean/readable worktree, and a strict
+`reviews/fix-result-NN.json` whose changed/no-change claim agrees with HEAD.
+Only then does Hive emit the WARN event `claude_completion_fallback` and
+continue. A failed audit write rejects the fallback.
+
+## June 29 incident findings
+
+The three observed failures prove that Hive did not see `.done`; they do not
+preserve enough process evidence to prove why. Source history shows that Hive
+already installed `.claude/settings.json` in both the task folder and launch
+cwd before June 29, so cwd hook-discovery drift is a plausible historical
+failure class but is not a conclusive root cause for these runs. The other
+concrete weakness was write ordering: the hook wrote `result.json` directly
+before touching `.done`, with no atomic publication, and the wrapper persisted
+no exit status. This release hardens both classes and guards the residual
+missing-signal case.
+
+If the issue is reproduced again, retain the generated settings from both
+directories, exact launch cwd, Stop-hook stdin, `result.json.tmp.*`, `.done`,
+`claude-exit-status`, tmux pane tail, session/PID state, and the
+`claude_completion_fallback` event. Without those observations, do not label a
+single discovery or timing mechanism as proven.
